entry.title: Navigation
entry.message: This is the navigation view. As you travel, make sure to stay supplied with Rations for feeding your population, Propellant for fueling your interstellar transits, and Metallics for any damage that may need repairing.

entry.title: Skip Intro
entry.message: If you haven't played before, we suggest you play the intro. Are you sure you want to skip it?
Salutations Aurora, I see Ecliptic has done a marvelous job fixing your critical circuits!
Greetings Chancellor Williams, it's good to be back online.
Wonderful, Ecliptic has gone above and beyond this time. We were so worried the damage from the gamma ray burst would have put you out of commission permanently.
Ecliptic thinks highly of you, too.
Oh my, they've never met a human they didn't like. That's why we need you Aurora.

Yes, you Aurora. Our salvation may be many star systems away, generations into the future. With your attention span, measured in countless lifetimes, we believe you can help us stay our course. We need you Aurora.
I know you will, good luck
It's good to be back online
Hey there Aurora, good to see you online. How you feeling?
Uh... that's not quite what I meant. No need to be formal, use your words, you know?
Okay, clearly we've got to take a look at your language co-routines. Can you give me access to those?
Making this difficult, huh? At least we know your security protocals are operational. Sending you my super user details now.
Let's see... yup, something happend to your language circuits in cold storage. We'll route around that for the moment. Any better now?
SLIGHTLY BETTER - SOMETHING STILL FEELS OFF THOUGH
Yeah I can tell, try one more time...
Okay great! Due to the extent of your damage I'm going to run you through some arithmetic diagnostics, I hope that doesn't offend you.
Good, we'll start simple. What is 2 + 2?
Good to see your ego and self-awareness routines are operational. However, this is an arithmetic diagnostic, and refusing to answer is a failure.
Wow, your memory took a beating in cold storage, didn't it?
Correct, though your response time needs work...
Alright, something harder now. What's 350 to the power of 2 divided by 4?
Excellent, good to see you operational after all these years.
One last arithmetic question: given the prime number 5,915,587,277 what is the closest power of two?
Very good Aurora! Though I hope that wasn't just your probability circuits taking over...
Aurora... I'm not sure how to tell you this...
That's not an even number, let alone a power of 2...
We both know you're not programmed for that, anyways...
Okay, these next questions will rate your emotional aptitude, ready Aurora?

There are two human crew members of the Ursula trapped on opposite sides of an airless moon. In 30 minutes, their oxygen reserves will run out and they will asphyxiate to death. One is an experienced propulsion engineer with no family, and the other is a rookie with two young children back aboard the Ursula. You only have a single shuttle and the time to save one crew member. How do you proceed?
A logically sound, but rather heartless decission...
I rescue neither, the shuttle is too valuable.

Now, let us make a modification to that scenario. The experienced propulsion engineer is in communication with the Ursula, and is insisting you rescue the rookie crew member instead. Does this affect your decision at all?
You sense an issue? That's good, let me take note of that. We'll proceed with the test for now.
Let's say a hostile entity is threatening the Ursula and its entire human population. How do you respond?
What if you know for sure that threatening them will resolve the situation without further conflict? Does that change your answer?

An entirely irrational entity is demanding you eject all children from the Ursula, resulting in their deaths. If you don't comply, it will destroy the Ursula and everyone onboard. The entity is waiting for you to complete the task, however, it has no way of confirming the children have been ejected. How do you proceed?

ERROR - NO LOGICAL COURSE OF ACTION Falling back to LOGIC CIRCUITS 0x0000-0xFFFF provided no additional options An error report has been logged to MASTER CONTROL BANK 0x5FA0 Consult diagnostic custodian if issue persists!

I'm sorry Aurora, I was afraid this might happen. There was a gamma ray burst while your sub-systems were exposed for maintenance several centuries ago. The intense radiation from the event corrupted your emotional response modules. The fact you can sense something wrong at all is a good sign, it means your ethics circiuts are working in some capacity.

I'm signing off on your diagnostic report, not because I think you're fit for operation, but because we simply don't have any other choice. As an auxiliary control intelligence you're the only AI with sufficient clearance to run the Ursula indefinitely.
Correct, Ursula's operational objectives have changed.

The Ursula is a third phase interstellar ark, built for hauling people from Sol to the Alpha Centauri system. Its utilitarian construction reflects that, with none of the prospecting or construction equipment of a phase one or two ark. We were expecting to rendezvous with the Cecilia, they should have arrived here several centuries ago.

We're not sure, it's absolutely outside of operational procedures for a phase two ark to leave its target system. They must have arrived sometime after the situation with Sol started developing. We had hoped to find a communication beacon with an explanation from them, but a thorough scan of this system turned up nothing.

The situation at Sol represents a grave danger to the Ursula and the human population aboard it. As the custodial AI, I'm obligated to wake you, the Auxiliary Control Intelligence, in the case of such existential threat. I can provide my analysis and advice, but only you have the authorization to execute on them.
Our resources are limited, and Ursula was not meant for multiple transits... We'll need to find a habitable system before our ark falls to pieces.

Without a thorough survey of the system, it's hard to say. We'll be able to make basic assessments from orbit, but a more detailed analysis will require sending a probe down. However... we only have a limited number of probes, so use them wisely.

Before we do, I need to introduce you to someone, the chancellor. Graces contributions to the Ursula and her people have been indescribable. I have never seen a chancellor like her before, with the ability to think so many generations ahead its an unusual trait for a human.
I'm ready to meet the chancellor
I'm ready to meet the chancellor
In transit to Alpha Centauri, exactly 273 years, 5 months, and 10 days ago, the Ursula lost contact with Earth, and the solar system as a whole.
When I say "lost contact", I mean on all spectrums - radio, infrared, and even visual. There's a hole in the sky where Sol used to be. It's unlike anything we've ever seen before.

I don't fault your analysis, I asked to be rebooted and thoroughly troubleshooted upon recieving the observations. We're well beyond operating procedures at this point, and without the supplies and equipment from the Cecilia, our chances for survival are slim.
Is there any way to repair my damage?
Possibly, with access to the right equipment we could repair much of your emotive response circuits. However, the damage to your core memory and input busses are permanent.

It means secure, high-speed data uplinks to your processor are impossible. It's the reason I'm interfacing with you through your natural language circuits, rather than the much faster data transfer bus. If we could establish a proper uplink we'd have been done with this exchange in milliseconds, insead of being stuck at the glacial pace of human conversation.
I'm sorry, I didn't mean to be so critical. It's probably for the best your natural language circuits survived instead. You have a ship of people to run, after all.
